Up in heaven, Paul Eeny was having his moral nature rectified, as did all new arrivals. He was a bit upset about having been murdered at first, but then he remembered that dear old Mart was up here somewhere and they’d be able to hang out soon. What had he really had to live for down there anyway? At least this way he wouldn’t scandalize everyone by getting really drunk at Martin’s funeral/celebration of life or whatever they did. Nor would he soberly annoy the widow by stealing the eulogical[@ I really liked “eulogical” ~C][@ 💯 ~M] show. Not that he probably would have done any of that anyway. He wondered about what sort of funeral he might have, whether anyone had found his body yet... In fact, how was he up here if he was still down there waiting to be cremated or whatever he’d agreed to in the small print of his life insurance policy?[@ I just find it amusing to imagine that the life insurance people care how your body is disposed of.] And would that policy be paid out to Angelica[@ Angelica Pulte Eeny a.k.a. A. Pulte Eeny a.k.a. Appletini] since its intended beneficiary had died first? Just then, a rectifying angel turned up one of the moral rectifier knobs and Paul lost his train of thought.

