A sharp, dull knock piercingly penetrated Thomas's[$Thomi?][@ pretty messed up how Prudence gets only an apostrophe but Thomas gets an apostrophe-s ~J] sensorium, instantly waking him up. He estimated he'd been asleep for three hours now and — as he always was after waking — he felt fit as a fiddle and chipper as a bull in a china shop.[@chip 'er? I 'ardly know 'er! ~M] He effortlessly, refreshèdly, put on his outerpants[$ overpants? überpants?] and then a shirt and then walked to the door and opened it.

"Good evening," said the fat man, anachronistically. He was a bit short, and wore a suit and some kind of formal hat. The fat man — understand: this man was 1970s fat; by the standards of, say, 2020s USA he was a non-euphemistic “pudgy”, or perhaps (as had in fact been occasionally remarked about him by certain more-corpulent friends on the occasion of seeing him disrobèd in the baths) “not fat” — the fat man, Regular Belasco, had about him a whimsical air of decay. An almost-affected world-weariness. "May I come in?" he asked Thomas.

"Come in," Thomas stepped aside.

The fat man came into the room, and produced a bottle of red white and two crystal goblets from under his arm. He set the latters on the table and decorked the former, pouring it in 'em. It made a pleasant pouring sound. It looked old.[$ old is good for a wine[$ much like for a teenager AMIRITE FELLAS? LADIES? THIS GUY KNOWS WHAT I'M TALKING ABOUT! (PUBESCENCE AND THE NATURAL END OF MAN) ~M][@ I can't tell if you intended the implied joke to be 'old is good for a teenager' or 'teenagers are good for a wine (whine)'. I think it wasn't 'old is teenager for a wine' so I'm going to go with that one. ~C[@ In making this annotation, it is clear I am not the 'THIS GUY' referred to elsewhere in this annotation tree. ~C]] ~M] "I hope you accept this apology for my interrupting your beauty sleep," he said.

"Oh boy!" said Thomas, licking his lips, imagining drinking this good-looking wine.

"Hey Thomas, do you know if there's ice?" asked Bus, slipping through the door that joined their two rooms.

"I have no idea, but you've come just in time for what promises to be a very significant conversation, Bus!"

"Oh, great!"

"I'm afraid I only brought the two glasses..." said the fat man.

"Luckily I brought my own, since I was looking for ice," said Bus, holding out his normal, non-wine glass. The fat man dutifully poured.

"Thomas, I have some urgently significant information for you," said the fat man, once all had sipped a little. He handed Thomas an envelope of photographs. "It concerns Lord Fitzthistlewits, and the case of the martini killer."[@ How does the fat man know this appellation!? ~C]

Thomas opened the envelope and leafed through them. All pictures of Lord Fitzthistlewits. Pictured at various parties and public events. In each, he was holding a martini glass.

"This is... just a guy drinking martinis. That doesn't mean anything. They're a completely normal drink, you know."

The fat man shook his head. "Look again, Thomas." [@My intention is not that Lord F is the martini killer — that would be ridiculous. But what happens next, to establish what the real connection is, is out of my hands.~M] [@ Perhaps Lord f will be wearing The same martini lapel pin that the martini killer is ~M]

[C; 786 words]

Thomas selected a photo at random, huffed on it, and buffed it with his newly-donned shirt. The ol' huff-n-buff. In so doing, a tiny detail caught his eye. "I say," he said, accurately[@ I mean, it's accurate because he is saying that. He said 'I say' and then he does. 'Accurately' here does not refer to the rest of his remark[@ Though it is accurate, presumably. ~C]. This seemed less clear on a second read through. ~C], "he's wearing the same martini lapel pin that the Martini Killer wears."

"True, but that's completely coincidental and unimportant."

"Oh."

"They are, as you yourself noted, a completely normal drink."

"I see."

"Barely worth remarking on. You've seen the martini killer?"

Thomas peered at the photo in his hand, at the others he'd set down, trying to see the significat[@ intentional. obscure noun form ~C], if it wasn't the lapel pin thing, which Thomas still felt might be related to the case. "Oh yes," he said distractedly. "Eclectic taste in music. He thinks I'm better at cribbagegammon than I am."

"Thomas was kidnapped by the martini killer a couple days ago and escaped just a few hours ago," Gus explained, taking pity on the fat man's look of bemusement[@ A word whose definition never seems to fit for me. I can't really picture a 'bemused' expression, even though I know what it means.[@ Or do I? ~C] ~C].

"Egad," muttered the fat man, removing the folded handkerchief from his suit pocket and wiping his brow[$ yes, really. He really did. I wouldn't have believed it if I hadn't written it with my own eyes.]. "Then we might not be safe here."

"Hmm?" Thomas glanced up from his perusal, frowning slightly. "Well, of course we aren't safe! You're participating in the investigation of an active serial killer, Mister...Belasco." He increased the intensity of his gaze at the still-visibly=nervous fat man and waved a dismissive hand. "You still have a good fifty-odd years left, if *that* eases your mind at all."

"R-really?" sputtered the fat man.

"Or hours. The Track sometimes confuses those," said Thomas vaguely, returning to his scrutiny of the photographs.

"Mr. Eeny did that too. Intuited my name, if not my time of death." Mr. Belasco refolded his handkerchief and replaced it in his pocket. "It's rather unsettling." His silhouette, cast by the rising sun streaming in through the south-east facing windows and framed rather strikingly by the frames of those self-same windows, mimicked his actions.

Only the fact that he was already standing (that pernicious habit!) kept Thomas from leaping to his feet. "You've seen Paul? He's alive!?"

The fat man gestured to the envelope. "He gave that to me on Tuesday evening[@ I looked up what day of the week Jan 1 2301 will be, assuming the day-of-the-week conventions are unchanged by whatever changed the base the year is expressed in. I ain't explaining that in the text—the readers can look it up if they want to, it's easy. ~C]. To bring to you, here at this time—"

"*These are from Paul?*" Thomas—it has to be said—shrieked. "Why didn't you mention that sooner?" he asked of both the fat man and the Track.

The fat man was growing a trifle irritated. "He said that they would have special significance to you, but the important information is obvious to anyone." He went on to point out and explain the important and obvious information[@ which is definitely known and not just being skipped over by a barely-competent hack to be figured out later by better writers :P ~C] [@ Maybe the martini killer is secretly in every photo, in sort of humorously obscured ways. Like being behind a fern ~M].

Thomas was barely listening. *Special significance...* But he'd already altered the order of the photos, their orientations... "Dunkle!" he snapped, interrupting Belasco. "Shuffle these."

"On it, boss." Gus drained his glass and started rearranging the photos any old how.

Thomas stared at him, unseeing, and ignoring the gaping fat man. He didn't doubt that there was some useful information in the photos' surface-level contents. But as soon as the fat man had relayed that the photos were from Paul, he'd been struck by a spasm of certainty: there was some other information in this envelope. Information only someone like him—like *them*—could possibly glean.

The time displayed on any visible clocks? The words legible on the banners in the pictures of civic events? Express the orientation of the picture in binary, from 00 to 11, and concatenate into an ascii string? Interpret the martinis as morse code, with the garnish (olive or lemon wedge) distinguishing the symbols and those martinis without garnish delimiting the letters?

*That one.*

Seriously?

*Yes!*[@ I'm intending this to be Thomas talking to himself, about his perceptions of the direction of The Track, rather than The Track communicating with Thomas in some quasi-verbal way. The difference might be largely a matter of perspective. ~C]

"Alrighty, boss, here you go." Gus passed the stack over to Thomas, who began flipping through them rapidly. Lemon, lemon, olive, none, olive...

In a few seconds, he'd come up with

..- --. .-.- .-.[@ I would like these to be center-justified, but I don't know how to do that. ~C]

"'Ugær'?" Thomas said aloud, returning from his quick jaunt through his memory palace. "Does that mean anything to either of you?"

The fat man stammered his failure to comprehend anything that was going on, least of all whatever Thomas had just said.

"'Ugæret' means 'unfermented' in Danish," Bustopher[@ You can change this if you wish, John. ~C] [@ note also that this is a perfect anagram of "u r gay" ~M] volunteered.

Thomas noted that for later consideration, but it seemed unlikely... "Reverse the polarity," he muttered. "I've always wanted occasion to mutter that."

